# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-super-bee
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The Dodge lineup was refreshed for the 1958 model year, continuing the three-line scheme of the 1955 Dodges with the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer was added as a new top-of-the-line model in spring.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The 1958 Dodges shared their basic mechanicals with the De Soto, but featured special styling.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The Coronet lasted through the 1959 model years.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 with 123 hp (92 kW), but the 325 in3 (5.3 L) *Red Ram (2bbl)/Super Red Ram (4bbl)* V8 was an option.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Coronets may typically be identified by a script mounted at the trailing edge of the belt-line stainless steel trim strip and a plain "up-sweep" molding of the rear fin trim, where both Royal and Custom Royal had a "dipping" element to the up-sweep trim.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were painted with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were club sedan, sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Lancers were further identified by a lance and shield emblem on each fin.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), and four-door hardtop (Lancer).
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] It came with the 350 in3 (5.7 L) Ram Fire V8 with a standard two-barrel carburetor, but the optional four-barrel carburetor delivered 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] A feature of the Custom Royal was its bumper-mounted exhaust ports which were only available on the Royal and Coronet models as part of the D-500 options.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Identifying exterior characteristics include Custom Royal script at the trailing edge of the belt-line molding, the pronounced check-mark, gold anodized Dodge block letters on the hood, and gold anodized Dodge script on the passenger side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized and had a unique rectangular pattern.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] All Custom Royals included a stainless molding above the bumper, on the flat edge below the trunk opening.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] To combat the recession of 1958, the Chrysler Corporation developed a program of spring specials to present a mid-year trim change on most of its makes.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The factory-produced spring specials for Dodge included a new wide, full-length belt line molding, grille emblem, fin end-caps, and a wide license plate escutcheon.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The Chrysler Corporation also shipped out all of these trim items individually to dealers so the dealers could "freshen up" the cars sitting on their lots.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Dealer-installed spring specials often include some elements of the factory spring special trim, but not always all.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] New exterior colors introduced for spring were Poppy Red, Frosted Turquoise, and Paris Rose.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Unrelated to spring specials, Dodge changed the headlight trim midway through the production run.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Later cars have a wide lower edge to the headlight trim while early cars have a thin lower edge.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Trying to boost sales, the **Regal Lancer** model was added in February and only available as a two-door hardtop with special colors, exterior trim and interior.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Four color combinations were available: bronze with white trim, bronze with black trim, black with bronze trim, and white with bronze trim.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] It featured special nameplates at the front of the side spear trim and heavy eyebrow trim.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Inside, Regal Lancers got their own interior with unique trim and door panels featuring molded armrests.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] A bronze instrument panel with textured aluminum inserts was a Regal Lancer exclusive.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The standard engine offered for Regal Lancers was the 350 cubic inch displacement "Ram Fire" V8.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Optional engine choices were the 361 cubic inch displacement **D-500** and **Super D-500** iterations.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The Suburban was Dodge's two-door station wagon in 1958.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] All station wagons came standard with the 350 Ram Fire engine.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The entry level four-door station wagon in 1958 was the Sierra.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Sierras came in either the six-passenger seat configuration or the nine-passenger "Spectator" seat configuration.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] From the exterior the nine-passenger configuration can be easily identified by the spare tire panel behind the rear wheel opening and the rubber step-spots on the rear bumper.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Custom Sierra wagons were the top-of-the-line station wagon offering for Dodge.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] As with Sierras, they were available as either six-passenger or Spectators.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The D-500 engine option was available across all models and all body styles including station wagons and the Regal Lancer.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The D-500 family of engines includes a four-barrel option, a dual four-barrel (Super D-500), and a Bendix electronic fuel injection system for the Super D-500.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The Bendix E.F.I. system proved to be troublesome and what few examples were built were recalled to be fitted with the normally aspirated dual four-barrel carburetor system.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] On passenger cars, the D-500 emblem was located on the driver side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] On station wagons, the D-500 emblem was located below the tail gate latch.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The 1958 D-500 emblem was unique to that year.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] All D-500s came with bumper mounted exhaust ports.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The California Highway patrol was so impressed with the performance of the new Dodge they ordered 200 vehicles with the D-500 option to be used on patrol duty.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] This was Chrysler's first move into specialized Police cars, and its success paved the way for decades of special police packages.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Dodge also offered a D-500-1 that was strictly for racing.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] It set several speed records on the sand at Daytona and the salt flats at Bonneville.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] They were also designed for NASCAR and drag racing.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The D-500-1 package was only available in a Coronet hardtop, convertible or two-door sedan with a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] Apart from the spring specials, Dodge offered a variety of paint and trim schemes for 1958.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The monotone, basic, and deluxe two-tones all used the "short" belt-line trim with model script behind the trailing edge.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The saddle two-tone used the 1957 full-length belt-line trim and placed the model script below the front fender belt-line trim.
[src:dodge-super-bee/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer had paint and trim unique to that model.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] This fourth-generation transmission by Mercedes-Benz replaced the older 4-speed 4G-Tronic transmission-family and its 5-speed derivative, and was replaced by the much more complex and costly 7-speed Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission (model **W7A 700** · type **722.9**) introduced in 2003.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] Due to its high torque capacity and lower cost, it was retained for turbocharged V8 and V12 engines, 4-cylinder applications and commercial vehicles for almost a decade.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] Production ended in 2020 with niche applications like Sprinter with petrol/CNG M111 engine and Jeep Wrangler.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] Activated by a toggle switch, Winter mode sets the gearbox to start off in 2nd gear, both in Drive and Reverse.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] This is designed to reduce wheelspin on icy surfaces.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] Also in "W" mode the transmission will shift at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] "S" mode is not sport but Sommer (German for summer) or Standard.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] With Jaguar XJR applications the switch is labeled "Sport." In regular driving mode the gearbox starts off in 2nd gear, both in Drive and Reverse, and will only engage 1st gear when triggered via the kickdown switch (Drive only).
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] While "Sport" mode is enabled the gearbox will always start off in 1st gear.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] Speedshift is a performance feature set for the Mercedes-Benz transmissions which includes manual mode and active downshifting.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] When cornering at high speed, the transmission maintains the same gear above a certain lateral acceleration level.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] It can also automatically downshift before overtaking.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] It was first used in 2001 Mercedes-Benz C 32 AMG and 2001 Mercedes-Benz SLK 32 AMG.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] A version with mechanical lock-up of the torque converter from first gear and steering-wheel-mounted shifter.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] AMG Speedshift is also used in 7G-Tronic transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] It was first used in 2002 Mercedes-Benz E 55 AMG, S 55 AMG, C55, CL 55 AMG.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] A version used in Mercedes-Benz SLR McLaren.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] The **5G-Tronic** is an electronically shifted 5-speed overdrive automatic transmission with torque converter lock-up, typically in gears 3, 4 and 5.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] The main objective in replacing the predecessor model was to improve vehicle fuel economy with extra speeds and a wider gear span to allow the engine speed level to be lowered (downspeeding), which is a decisive factor in improving energy efficiency and thus reducing fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] In addition, the lower engine speed level improves the noise-vibration-harshness comfort and the exterior noise is reduced.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] The need of 2 housings and 2 different controls turn out the **W5A 030** as the least economically designed automatic transmission ever manufactured for passenger cars.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] This was only possible thanks to computer-aided design.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] The 5G-Tronic is the 1st generation in which in-line epicyclic gearing have been combined with parallel epicyclic gearing.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] The resulting progress is reflected in an even better ratio between the number of gears and the number of components used compared to all layouts previously used by Mercedes-Benz.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] That is why Mercedes-Benz refers to them as **NAG 1 (N**ew **A**utomatic Gearbox **G**eneration, starting with type 722.6 as generation **1**).
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] With 9 main components, it saves 2 components compared to the W5A 030.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] The most obvious flaw of the gearset concept is the second gear, which is clearly too short, but this affected all Mercedes-Benz transmissions, especially automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] The 7G-Tronic in 2003 was the first to remedy this situation.
[src:dodge-super-bee/5g-tronic] As shown in the assessment table below, another drawback of the gearset concept is the significant reduction in speed increase in 5th gear.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Hines was born in Erie, Pennsylvania, to Edward and Willie (Chandler) Hines.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] He had a twin brother, Edward, and a sister Elizabeth.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Born with a severely deformed spine, the result of spinal kyphosis, he was unable to stand completely upright.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] At age two, he was sent to an Erie hospital, where he underwent surgery to remove two vertebrae.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] The hospital recommended he be sent to a special camp, where he was laid on a board in the sun all day for seven months, returning over the course of two and a half years; it helped relieve the unusual curvature.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Soon after Hines was initially released from hospital, his father died of tuberculosis.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Hines' mother moved to Detroit, Michigan to work, while her children were sent to be raised by their grandmother in Jackson, Tennessee.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] In 1932, the Hines children went to Detroit.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] In high school, Hines preferred art and shop classes to academics, and 1941, while in Grade 11, dropped out to rent a garage in Ecorse, Michigan, where he set up a custom shop.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] It was there he began working with lead body filler.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] His first project was a 1934 Ford, fitted with a flathead V8 with milled heads.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] He opened a gas station in Lincoln Park, Michigan, with an attached custom shop later the same year.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] His first custom, built in 1941, was a 1941 Buick, with molded fenders, widened rocker panels, cut-down doors (a Hines trademark), fender skirts, Appleton spotlight, and single-bar flipper hubcaps; he repainted the original turquoise to red, claiming every custom should be red with a white interior.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] He would later add a tailfin in the center of the trunklid, a feature earning so much ridicule, he changed back to a stock lid.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] He went on to build and race a midget powered by a 60 hp (45 kW) flathead.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] In the late 1940s, Hines did bodywork and painting for Vick Sawitskas' Nash dealership in Wyandotte, Michigan.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Hines finally opened his own dedicated custom shop in Lincoln Park early in the 1950s.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] It was there in 1957 he built *Lil' Bat*, a 1950 Ford with a 6 in (150 mm) chop, frenched headlights, the grille bar from a 1951 Ford Meteor, and large fins fitted with taillights from a 1956 Ford.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] The car made its debut at the 1959 Detroit Autorama, and was featured on the cover of *Rod & Custom* Magazine in March 1959.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] When he visited George Barris' shop driving this car in 1958, Barris' shop manager, Gene Simmons (not to be confused with the artist), hired him immediately on the strength of the work.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Hines moved back to Detroit just before Christmas 1959,. setting up shop where he did several custom jobs and specialized in candy paint jobs.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] He served as mentor to customizers Richard Sawitskas, better known as Dick Dean, and Detroit's Alexander Brothers.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Hines returned to California in October 1960, setting up Bill Hines Kustom Auto in Lynwood, next door to Eddie Martinez's shop.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] In 1962, Hines installed one of the first hydraulic lift systems on Tats Gotanda's Candy blue 1959 Chevrolet Impala; this became known as the *Buddah Buggy*, and was Hines' most famous custom project.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Hines also collaborated with Joe Bailon to produce the *Panthermobile* in 1969.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] Hines worked without drawing plans, able to, for instance, construct a custom working convertible top from scratch without them.
[src:dodge-super-bee/alexander-brothers-auto-customizers] While living in Garden Grove, California, in 2015, Hines suffered a heart attack.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:dodge-super-bee/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] An **axle** or **axletree** is a central shaft for a rotating wheel or gear.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] On wheeled vehicles, the axle may be fixed to the wheels, rotating with them, or fixed to the vehicle, with the wheels rotating around the axle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In the former case, bearings or bushings are provided at the mounting points where the axle is supported.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In the latter case, a bearing or bushing sits inside a central hole in the wheel to allow the wheel or gear to rotate around the axle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Sometimes, especially on bicycles, the latter type of axle is referred to as a *spindle*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] On cars and trucks, several senses of the word *axle* occur in casual usage, referring to the shaft itself, its housing, or simply any transverse pair of wheels.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Strictly speaking, a shaft that rotates with the wheel, being either bolted or splined in fixed relation to it, is called an *axle* or *axle shaft*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] However, in looser usage, an entire assembly including the surrounding axle housing (typically a casting) is also called an *axle*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] An even broader (somewhat figurative) sense of the word refers to every pair of parallel wheels on opposite sides of a vehicle, regardless of their mechanical connection to each other and to the vehicle frame or body.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Thus, transverse pairs of wheels in an independent suspension may be called an *axle* in some contexts.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] This very loose definition of "axle" is often used in assessing toll roads or vehicle taxes, and is taken as a rough proxy for the overall weight-bearing capacity of a vehicle, and its potential for causing wear or damage to roadway surfaces.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Axles are an integral component of most practical wheeled vehicles.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The solid axles (housings) in this system must also bear the weight of the vehicle plus any cargo.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] A non-driving axle, such as the front beam axle in heavy-duty trucks and some two-wheel drive light trucks and vans, will have no shaft, and serves only as a suspension and steering component.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Conversely, many front-wheel drive cars have a one-piece rear beam axle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In other types of suspension systems, the axles serve only to transmit driving torque to the wheels: the position and angle of the wheel hubs is made independent from the axles by the function of the suspension system.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] This is typical of the independent suspensions found on most newer cars, and even SUVs, and on the front of many light trucks.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] An exception to this rule is the independent (rear) swing axle suspension, wherein the half-axles are also load-bearing suspension arms.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Independent drive-trains still need differentials (or diffs), but without fixed axle-housing tubes attached.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The diff may be attached to the vehicle frame or body, and/or be integrated with the transmission (or gearbox) in a combined transaxle unit.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The axle (half-)shafts then transmit driving torque to the wheels, usually via constant-velocity joints.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Like a full floating axle system, the drive shafts in a front-wheel-drive independent suspension system do not support any vehicle weight.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] A straight axle is a single rigid shaft connecting a wheel on the left side of the vehicle to a wheel on the right side.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The axis of rotation fixed by the axle is common to both wheels.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Such a design can keep the wheel positions steady under heavy stress, and can therefore support heavy loads.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Straight axles are used on trains (that is, locomotives and railway wagons), for the rear axles of commercial trucks, and on heavy-duty off-road vehicles.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The axle can optionally be protected and further reinforced by enclosing the length of the axle in a housing.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In split-axle designs, the wheel on each side is attached to a separate shaft.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Modern passenger cars have split-drive axles.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In some designs, this allows independent suspension of the left and right wheels, and therefore a smoother ride.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Even when the suspension is not independent, split axles permit the use of a differential, allowing the left and right drive wheels to be driven at different speeds as the automobile turns, improving traction and extending tire life.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] A tandem axle is a group of two or more axles situated close together.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Truck designs use such a configuration to provide a greater weight capacity than a single axle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Semi-trailers usually have a tandem axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Axles are typically made from SAE grade 41xx steel or SAE grade 10xx steel.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] SAE grade 41xx steel is commonly known as "chrome-molybdenum steel" (or "chrome-moly") while SAE grade 10xx steel is known as "carbon steel".
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The primary differences between the two are that chrome-moly steel is significantly more resistant to bending or breaking, and is very difficult to weld with tools normally found outside a professional welding shop.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] An axle that is driven by the engine or prime mover is called a *drive axle*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Modern front-wheel drive cars typically combine the transmission (gearbox and differential) and front axle into a single unit called a *transaxle*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The drive axle is a split axle with a differential and universal joints between the two half axles.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Each half axle connects to the wheel by use of a constant velocity (CV) joint which allows the wheel assembly to move freely vertically as well as to pivot when making turns.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In rear-wheel drive cars and trucks, the engine turns a driveshaft (also called a *propeller shaft* or *tailshaft*) which transmits the rotational force to a drive axle at the rear of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The drive axle may be a live axle, but modern rear-wheel drive automobiles generally use a split axle with a differential.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In this case, one half-axle or half-shaft connects the differential with the left rear wheel, a second half-shaft does the same with the right rear wheel; thus the two half-axles and the differential constitute the rear axle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The front drive axle is providing the force to drive the truck.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In fact, only one wheel of that axle is actually moving the truck and trailer down the road.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Some simple vehicle designs, such as leisure go-karts, may have a single driven wheel where the drive axle is a split axle with only one of the two shafts driven by the engine, or else have both wheels connected to one shaft without a differential (kart racing).
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] However, other go-karts have two rear drive wheels too.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Some dump trucks and trailers may be configured with a lift axle (also known as an *airlift axle* or *drop axle*), which may be mechanically raised or lowered.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The axle is lowered to increase the weight capacity, or to distribute the weight of the cargo over more wheels, for example, to cross a weight-restricted bridge.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] When not needed, the axle is lifted off the ground to save wear on the tires and axle, and to increase traction in the remaining wheels, and to decrease fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Lifting an axle also alleviates lateral scrubbing of the additional axle in very tight turns, allowing the vehicle to turn more readily.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In some situations, the removal of pressure from the additional axle is necessary for the vehicle to complete a turn at all.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Several manufacturers offer computer-controlled airlifts so that the dead axles are automatically lowered when the main axle reaches its weight limit.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The dead axles can still be lifted by the press of a button if needed, for better maneuverability.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Lift axles were in use in the early 1940s.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Initially, the axle was lifted by a mechanical device.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Soon hydraulics replaced the mechanical lift system.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] One of the early manufacturers was Zetterbergs, located in Östervåla, Sweden.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The liftable tandem drive axle was invented in 1957 by the Finnish truck manufacturer Vanajan Autotehdas, a company sharing history with Sisu Auto.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] A full-floating axle carries the vehicle's weight on the axle casing, not the half-shafts; they serve only to transmit torque from the differential to the wheels.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] They "float" inside an assembly that carries the vehicle's weight.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Thus the only stress it must endure is torque (not lateral bending force).
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Full-floating axle shafts are retained by a flange bolted to the hub, while the hub and bearings are retained on the spindle by a large nut.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] In contrast, a semi-floating design carries the weight of the vehicle on the axle shaft itself; there is a single bearing at the end of the axle housing that carries the load from the axle and that the axle rotates through.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] To be "semi-floating" the axle shafts must be able to "float" in the housing, bearings and seals, and not subject to axial "thrust" and/or bearing preload.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] A true semi-floating axle assembly places no side loads on the axle housing tubes or axle shafts.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] Axles that are pressed into ball or tapered roller bearings, which are in turn retained in the axle housings with flanges, bolts, and nuts do not "float" and place axial loads on the bearings, housings, and only a short section of the shaft itself, that also carries all radial loads.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The full-floating design is typically used in most ¾- and 1-ton light trucks, medium-duty trucks, and heavy-duty trucks.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The overall assembly can carry more weight than a semi-floating or non-floating axle assembly because the hubs have two bearings riding on a fixed spindle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] A full-floating axle can be identified by a protruding hub to which the axle shaft flange is bolted.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The semi-floating axle setup is commonly used on half-ton and lighter 4×4 trucks in the rear.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] This setup allows the axle shaft to be the means of propulsion, and also support the weight of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The main difference between the full- and semi-floating axle setups is the number of bearings.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The semi-floating axle features only one bearing, while the full-floating assembly has bearings on both the inside and outside of the wheel hub.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] To remove the semi-floating axle, the wheel must be removed first; if such an axle breaks, the wheel is most likely to come off the vehicle.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] The semi-floating design is found under most ½-ton and lighter trucks, as well as in SUVs and rear-wheel-drive passenger cars, usually being smaller or less expensive models.
[src:dodge-super-bee/axle] A benefit of a full-floating axle is that even if an axle shaft (used to transmit torque or power) breaks, the wheel will not come off, preventing serious accidents.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Named after the town of Brampton in Cumberland, England, Brampton was incorporated as a village in 1853 and as a town in 1873, and became a city in 1974.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The modern City of Brampton was formed following an amalgamation of several surrounding townships and communities.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The city was once known as "The Flower Town of Canada", a title referring to its abundance of greenhouses and strong floriculture industry in the 1860s.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It maintains the term "Flower City" as its slogan.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Despite being built as a car-centric city, Brampton has a significant transit system, with a ridership of 49,200,800, or about 226,500 per weekday as of the second quarter of 2024.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Before the arrival of British settlers, the Mississaugas of the Credit First Nation held 648,000 acres (262,000 ha) of the land north to the head of the Lake Purchase lands and extending to the unceded territory of the Chippewa of Lakes Huron and Simcoe.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] European settlers began to arrive in the area in the late 18th century.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In October 1818, the chief of the Mississaugas of the Credit First Nation signed Treaty 19, also known as the Ajetance Purchase, surrendering the area to the British Crown.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Prior to the 1830s, most business in Chinguacousy Township took place at Martin Salisbury's tavern.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] One mile from the corner of Hurontario Street and the 5th Sideroad (now Main and Queen Streets in the centre of Brampton), William Buffy's tavern was the only significant building.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] At the time, the intersection was referred to as "Buffy's Corners".
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] By 1834, John Elliott laid out the area in lots for sale, calling it "Brampton", which was soon adopted by others.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1853, a small agricultural fair was set up by the newly initiated County Agricultural Society of the County of Peel and was held at the corner of Main and Queen streets.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Grains, produce, roots, and dairy products were up for sale.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Horses and cattle, along with other lesser livestock, were also sold at the market.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] This agricultural fair eventually became the modern Brampton Fall Fair.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In that same year, Brampton was incorporated as a village.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1866, the town became the county seat and the location of the Peel County Courthouse which was built in 1865–66; a three-storey County jail was added at the rear in 1867.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Edward Dale, an immigrant from Dorking, England, established a flower nursery in Brampton shortly after his arrival in 1863.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Dale's Nursery had become the town's largest and most prominent employer, developed a flower grading system, and established a global export market for its products.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The company chimney was a town landmark, until Brampton Town Council allowed it to be torn down in 1977.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] At its height, the company had 140 greenhouses, and was the largest cut flower business in North America, producing 20 million blooms and introducing numerous rose and orchid cultivar to the market.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It also spurred the development of other nurseries in the town.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Forty-eight hothouse flower nurseries once did business in the town.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In January 1867, Peel County separated from the County of York, a union which had existed since 1851.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] By 1869, Brampton had a population of 1,800.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The town of Brampton had problems with inadequate water supply in its early years, as the town relied on shallow wells for not just residential water, but commercial use and fire-fighting.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] A Brampton Water Works filtration plant was built south of the lake, located where present-day White Spruce Park is.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Today the city uses water from other sources, and Heart Lake is now the centerpiece of Heart Lake Conservation Area.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] A federal grant had enabled the village to found its first public library in 1887, which included 360 volumes from the Mechanic's Institute (established in 1858).
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1907, the library received a grant from the Carnegie Foundation, set up by United States steel magnate and philanthropist Andrew Carnegie, to build a new, expanded library; it serves several purposes, featuring the Brampton Library.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Carnegie libraries were built on the basis of communities coming up with matching funds and guaranteeing maintenance.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Gage (owner of Gage Publishing, a publishing house specializing in school textbooks) purchased a 3.25-acre (1.32 ha) portion of the gardens and lawns of the Alder Lea estate (now called Alderlea) that had been built on Main Street by Kenneth Chisholm in 1867 to 1870.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] (Chisholm, a merchant and founding father of Brampton, had been the Town reeve, then warden of Peel County, then MPP for Brampton and eventually, Registrar of Peel County.) Gage donated 1.7 acres (0.69 ha) of the property to the town, with a specific condition that it be made into a park.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Citizens donated $1,054 and the town used the funds to purchase extra land to ensure a larger park.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] A group of regional farmers in Brampton had trouble getting insurance from city-based companies.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] After several meetings in Clairville Hall, they decided to found the County of Peel Farmers Mutual Fire Insurance Company.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1955, when the company moved to its third and current location, 103 Queen Street West, it took the new name of Peel Mutual Insurance Company.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It reigns as the longest-running company in modern Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Harmsworth Decorating Centre was established in 1890, as Harmsworth and Son, operated out of the family's house on Queen Street West.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The current location was purchased on September 1, 1904, after a fire destroyed their original store.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Purchased for $1,400, the 24 Main Street South location is the longest-operating retail business in what is now Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1963, the town established *The Flower Festival of Brampton*, which was based on the *Rose Festival* in Portland, Oregon, United States.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It began to market itself as the *Flower Town of Canada*.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1974, the two townships of Chinguacousy and Toronto Gore were incorporated into Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In a revival of this theme, on June 24, 2002, the City Council established the "Flower City Strategy", to promote a connection to its flower-growing heritage.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The intention was to inspire design projects and community landscaping to beautify the city, adopt a sustainable environmental approach, and to protect its natural and cultural heritage.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Rose Theatre was named in keeping with this vision and is to serve as a cultural institution in the city.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In addition, the city participates in the national Communities in Bloom competition as part of that strategy.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Old Shoe Factory, located at 57 Mill Street North, once housed the Hewetson Shoe Company.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It was listed as a historical property under the Ontario Heritage Act in 2008.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Today it is occupied by various small businesses.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The lobby and hallways retain details from 1907.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Walls are decorated with pictures and artifacts of local Brampton history and old shoemaking equipment.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] A self-guided historical walking tour of downtown Brampton called "A Walk Through Time" is available at Brampton City Hall and online at no cost.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Planned as an innovative "new town", Bramalea was developed in the 1950s immediately east of the Town of Brampton in Chinguacousy Township.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] He sold the land to Brampton Leasing (the former name of the developer) and built one of Bramalea's first houses on Dixie Road.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The community was developed according to its detailed master plan, which included provisions for a parkland trail system and a "downtown" to include essential services and a shopping centre.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The downtown's centrepiece was the Civic Centre, built in 1972 to include the city hall and library.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Directly across Team Canada Drive, a shopping centre, Bramalea City Centre was built.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] These developments were connected by a long tunnel, planned to provide protection from winter weather.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The tunnel has long since been closed due to safety issues.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1974, the Ontario provincial government decided to update Peel County's structure.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It amalgamated several towns and villages into the new City of Mississauga.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] While only Huttonville and Churchville still exist as identifiable communities, other names like Claireville are re-emerging as names of new developments.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The province converted Peel County into the Regional Municipality of Peel.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton retained its role as the administrative centre of Peel Region, which it already had as county seat.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The regional council chamber, the Peel Regional Police force, the public health department, and the region's only major museum, the Peel Art Gallery, Museum and Archives, are all located in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] This change had its critics among those with a strong sense of local identities.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Bramptonians feared urban sprawl would dissolve their town's personality.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Bramalea residents took pride in the built-from-scratch and organised structure that had come with their new satellite city and did not want to give it up.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Others in Bramalea accept they are part of Brampton, and they make up a "tri-city" area: the original Brampton, Heart Lake, Bramalea.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1972, Chinguacousy built a new civic centre in Bramalea.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Two years later, when Brampton and Chinguacousy merged, the new city's council was moved from its modest downtown Brampton locale to the Bramalea building.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The library systems of Brampton and Chinguacousy were merged, resulting in a system of four locations.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Some have questioned the future of Peel Region as encompassing all of Brampton, Mississauga, and Caledon.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Mississauga council, led by Mayor Hazel McCallion, voted to become a single-tier municipality and asked the provincial government to be separated from Peel Region.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] They argued the city has outgrown the need for a regional layer of government, and that Mississauga is being held back by supporting Brampton and Caledon with its municipal taxes.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In the early 1980s, Cineplex Odeon closed the Capitol Theatre in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The City bought the facility in 1981 under the leadership of councillor Diane Sutter.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It adapted the former vaudeville venue and movie house as a performing arts theatre, to be used also as a live music venue.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Renovations and maintenance were expensive.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1983, Toronto consultants Woods Gordon reported to the City that, rather than continue "pouring money" into the Heritage, they should construct a new 750-seat facility with up-to-date features.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] This recommendation was adopted, and the city designated the 2005–06 season as the Heritage Theatre's "grand finale" season.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The city funded construction of the new Rose Theatre, which opened in September 2006.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Carabram was founded in 1982, the result of volunteers from different ethnic communities wanting to organize a festival celebrating diversity and cross-cultural friendship.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The name was loosely related to Toronto's Caravan Festival of Cultures.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Carabram's first event featured Italian, Scots, Ukrainian, and West Indian pavilions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] By 2003, the fair had 18 pavilions attracting 45,000 visitors.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton has grown to become one of the most diverse cities in Canada.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1996, the city was 13% South Asian and 8.2% black.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] By 2016, the South Asian community grew significantly to represent 44.3% of the city's population, while the black population grew to 14%.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Responding to a growing multi-cultural population, the Peel Board of Education introduced evening English as a Second Language (ESL) classes at high schools.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Originally taught by volunteers, the classes eventually were scheduled as daytime courses taught by paid instructors.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In the 1980s, the public and Catholic board expanded its language programs, offering night classes in 23 languages.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] These were introduced due to requests by parents, who wanted their children to learn their ancestral languages and heritage.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In the late 1980s, Mayor Ken Whillans gained approval and funding for the construction of a new city hall in Brampton's downtown.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The facility was designed by local architects and built on the site of a former bus terminal.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Whillians did not get to see the opening of the new hall in June 1991 because of his death in August 1990.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Its completion brought the municipal government back to downtown Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The facility expanded in 2014 with the addition of a nine-storey tower at 41 George Street and is connected to the original building by a glass walkway called Heritage Way.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1991, development of another new town, Springdale, began.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1999, development started to appear as far north as the city's border with Caledon along Mayfield Road.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Region designated this border as the line of demarcation for urban development until 2021, although development already began spilling north of Mayfield in the late 2010s.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Part of the boundary between Brampton and Vaughan is also nearly completely urbanized.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Changes continue to reflect the growth of the city.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1992 the City purchased the Brampton Fairgrounds, to be used for other development.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Agricultural Society relocated in 1997 outside the boundaries of the city to Heart Lake and Old School roads.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton's 2003 Sesquicentennial celebrations boosted community spirit, reviving the tradition of a summer parade (with 100 floats), and creating other initiatives.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] To commemorate the town's history, the city under Mayor Fennell reintroduced floral projects to the community.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] These have included more plantings around town, the revival in 2005 of the city Parade, and participation in the Canada Communities in Bloom project.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton has a total land area of 265 square kilometres (102 sq mi).
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It follows the line as far east as the former Indian Line (today a private access road), turns back north along it to briefly border Toronto (Etobicoke), towards the intersection of Steeles Ave. and Albion Road/Highway 50.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton features a continental climate (Köppen climate classification: *Dfa*) which is typical of the rest of the Greater Toronto Area.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Data from Toronto Pearson International Airport, located 10.55 km (6.56 mi) east.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Data is from Georgetown, located 10.93 km (6.79 mi) south-southwest.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In the 2021 Canadian census conducted by Statistics Canada, Brampton had a population of 656,480 living in 182,472 of its 189,086 total private dwellings, a change of 10.6% from its 2016 population of 593,638.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] At its growth rate of 10.6% since the 2016 census, Brampton was the fastest-growing of Canada's largest 25 municipalities.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In the 2021 Canadian census, people of South Asian origin were the largest ethnocultural group in Brampton—accounting for 52.4% of the population.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The city is ethnically diverse with approximately 60% of Brampton's residents being foreign-born.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 2021, the most reported religion among the population was Christianity (35.7%), with Catholicism (17.3%) making up the largest denomination.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] 10.3% of the population did not identify with a particular religion.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Toronto Ontario Temple for the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church) is located in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The 2021 census found that English was the mother tongue of 42.9% of the population.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Companies with headquarters in Brampton include MDA Space Missions, which will be building the CanadaArm 3.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Loblaw Companies Ltd., Chrysler Canada Brampton Assembly Plant, Gamma-Dynacare Medical Laboratories, Mandarin Restaurant, Brita, Shoppers Drug Mart, Canon, Canadian Blood Services, Sleep Country Canada and Clorox.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] William Osler Health System employs approximately 5,000 at its Brampton Civic and Peel Memorial campuses.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Lululemon, and Pet Valu have their main GTA distribution centres in the city.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Wolseley Plumbing built a distribution Center and showroom in Brampton in 2024.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Alstom has an assembly plant in Brampton to fulfil their contract with Metrolinx to build Alstom Citadis Spirit LRV cars for the TTC Finch West (ordered in 2017 with delivery beginning 2021 to be completed by 2023), Hurontario and Eglinton LRT lines.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Hurontario LRT maintenance facility is currently being built in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] It is also the location of the Canadian Forces Army Reserve unit The Lorne Scots (Peel, Dufferin and Halton Regiment).
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] An automobile manufacturing facility was opened by American Motors (AMC) in 1960 as the Brampton Assembly Plant.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 1986, AMC developed a new, state-of-the-art operation at Bramalea.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] After AMC was acquired by Chrysler in 1987, AMC's Canadian division and its plants were absorbed; the older facility in Brampton closed in 1992.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The newest factory was renamed Brampton Assembly; it is one of the city's largest employers, with almost 4,000 workers when running at capacity.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Algoma University at Brampton School of Business & Economics offers courses at Market Square Business Centre, 24 Queen Street East.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The closest universities to Brampton (offering a wider range of programs) include York University in north Toronto and University of Toronto Mississauga.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Along with that, Sheridan College's Davis Campus is another major public higher education institution serving Brampton which also has campuses in Oakville and Mississauga.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 2017, Davis added the Skilled Trades Centre, for training in skilled trades and apprenticeship programs, previously offered in Oakville.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] A plan by Toronto Metropolitan University, in partnership with Sheridan College was to establish a new campus in Brampton with a goal of opening in 2022 with $90 million in funding offered by the provincial government in April 2018.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] On 23 October 2018 however, the new Provincial government (elected in June) withdrew the funding for plans such as this, effectively cancelling the project.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 2022, the university, now renamed as Toronto Metropolitan, announced plans to open a medical school in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton City Council gifted the university the Bramalea Civic Centre and most of the land it resides for this purpose.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Two main school boards operate in Brampton: the Peel District School Board, which operates secular anglophone public schools, and Dufferin-Peel Catholic District School Board, which operates Catholic anglophone public schools.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Under the Peel District School Board, the secondary schools are Bramalea, Brampton Centennial, Central Peel, Chinguacousy, Fletcher's Meadow, Harold M.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brathwaite, Heart Lake, Louise Arbour, Mayfield, North Park, Judith Nyman, Sandalwood Heights, Turner Fenton, David Suzuki, Castlebrooke Secondary School, and Jean Augustine, one of the newest.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] A total of 85 elementary and middle schools feed these high schools in the city.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Under the Dufferin-Peel Catholic District School Board, the secondary schools are Cardinal Leger, Holy Name of Mary, Notre Dame, St.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] A total of 44 Catholic elementary and middle schools feed these high schools in the city.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The *Conseil scolaire Viamonde* operates secular Francophone schools serving the area.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The *Conseil scolaire catholique MonAvenir* operates Catholic Francophone schools serving the area.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Several cultural entities in the city operate under the umbrella of the Brampton Arts Council.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Located in the city is the Peel Art Gallery, Museum and Archives (PAMA, formerly the Peel Heritage Complex), which is run by the Region of Peel.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Rose Theatre (originally the Brampton Performing Arts Centre), opened in September 2006.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The city had expected the facility to generate $2.7 million in economic activity the first year, growing to $19.8 million by the fifth year.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Rose Theatre far surpassed projections, attracting more than 137,000 patrons in its inaugural year, which exceeded its five-year goal.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The arrival of so many new patrons downtown has stimulated the development of numerous new businesses nearby.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] A new Fountain Stage was unveiled in June 2008 at the nearby Garden Square.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton has eight library branches to serve its population.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Festivals in the city include the annual Festival of Literary Diversity, a literary festival devoted to writers from underrepresented groups such as people of colour and LGBTQ writers.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Peel Art Gallery, Museum and Archives (PAMA) in Brampton includes a museum, art gallery, and archives.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Since opening in 1968, the art gallery section (previously known as the Art Gallery of Peel) has exhibited local, national, and international artists, both contemporary and historical from their permanent collection.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The City of Brampton's long-standing heritage conservation program was recognised with the 2011 Lieutenant Governor's Ontario Heritage Award for Community Leadership.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In 2010, the city received an 'honourable mention' under the same provincial awards program.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Major shopping areas include Bramalea City Centre, Shoppers World, and "big box centre" Trinity Commons.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The downtown area has some retail; the Centennial Mall and the Brampton Mall are also of note.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton was one of the first areas where Rogers Cable offered its service.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The city started a community access channel in the 1970s, which still operates.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] While some programs on the channel are produced in its Brampton studios, most are based in its Mississauga location.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Christian specialty channel Vertical TV is based in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton is the official city of license for two radio stations, CHLO and CFNY.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Both stations address their programming toward the entire Greater Toronto Area rather than exclusively to Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] CFNY was located upstairs at 83 Kennedy Road until moving to Toronto in 1996.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton has been home to minor professional sports franchises at the CAA Centre, formerly the Powerade Centre.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] From 2013 to 2015, the Brampton A's played in the National Basketball League of Canada, but relocated to Orangeville, Ontario, to decrease costs of operations of switching the arena floor from ice hockey to basketball.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] From 2013 to 2020, the Brampton Beast played in the Central Hockey League and ECHL, but ceased operations during the COVID-19 pandemic in February 2021 after having not been able to play since March 2020.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The numerous sporting venues and activities includes the outdoor ice path for skating through Gage Park.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Chinguacousy Park includes a ski lift, a curling club, and Tennis Centre for multi-season activities.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In the summer, amateur softball leagues abound.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Crowds line the beaches at Professor's Lake for the annual outdoor "shagging" display.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Since 1967, the Brampton Canadettes have hosted the annual Brampton Canadettes Easter Tournament in hockey.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] William Osler Health System operates two health facilities in the city.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Grenville & William Davis Courthouse which houses branches for the Ontario Court of Justice and the Ontario Superior Court of Justice, is located at 7755 Hurontario Street (Hurontario Street at County Court).
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Brampton Jail is in the city it's now defunct and has turned into a museum.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The Roy McMurtry Youth Centre is a juvenile detention centre located in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Local transit is provided by Brampton Transit, with connections to other systems such as MiWay, York Region Transit, GO Transit, and Toronto Transit Commission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton Transit also operates a bus rapid transit system, "Züm" (pronounced Zoom), along Main/Hurontario Streets, Steeles Avenue, Queen Street/Highway 7, Bovaird Drive–Airport Road, and Queen Street West–Mississauga Road, which form the backbone to its bus network.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] There is GO Bus service to York University and subway stations at Yorkdale Mall and York Mills in Toronto.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] There are three GO Train stations in Brampton along the Kitchener line: Bramalea, Brampton and Mount Pleasant.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Both Canadian National Railway (CN) and the Orangeville-Brampton Railway short line (formerly part of the Canadian Pacific Railway (CP) line) run through the city.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] CN's Intermodal Yards are located east of Airport Road between Steeles and Queen Street East.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] The CN Track from Toronto's Union Station is used by the Kitchener GO Transit Rail Corridor providing commuter rail to and from Toronto with rail station stops at Bramalea, Downtown Brampton, and Mount Pleasant.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Via Rail connects through Brampton as part of the Quebec City-Windsor Corridor.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Canada's busiest airport, Toronto Pearson International Airport (CYYZ), is located near Brampton, in Mississauga.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] For general aviation, the city is served by the privately owned Brampton Airport (CNC3), located to the north of the city in neighbouring Caledon.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] There is also a registered helipad Brampton National D (CPC4) located near the Brampton/Vaughan border, at Countryside Drive and Coleraine Drive.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Brampton is served by several major transportation routes: Highway 401 from Toronto is a short distance south in Mississauga, and can be reached by Highway 410, which runs north–south through the middle of the city.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Highway 407 runs along the southern portion of the city, just north of the boundary with Mississauga.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Steeles Avenue, which runs north of the 407, is a thoroughfare continuing from Toronto.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Queen Street is the city's main east–west street.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Farther north, Bovaird Drive is another main artery.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Sections of both Queen (eastern portion) and Bovaird (western portion) were part the former Highway 7, (now Regional Road 107), with Highway 410 being the route followed between the two streets.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] Main Street, part of the historic road, Hurontario Street (as well as Hurontario proper in the northern and southern parts of the city), and formerly Highway 10, is the city's main north–south artery.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p01] In the east end, Airport Road is a busy artery that is used as a route north to Wasaga Beach, a popular beach resort town.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Four people from Brampton have received the Order of Canada: Robert William Bradford, former Director of the National Aviation Museum; Michael F.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Clarke, director at Evergreen, the Yonge Street Mission for street youth in Toronto; Howard Pawley, professor and former Premier of Manitoba; and William G.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Three Canadian premiers got their start in Brampton; Premiers Tobias Norris and Howard Pawley OC of Manitoba, and "Brampton Billy", Ontario premier William Grenville Davis CC.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Other notable politicians include John Coyne, and Conservative opposition leader Gordon Graydon.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Alberta politician and businessman Sir James A.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Lougheed was born in Brampton, and served 30 years in Senate; Regina mayor David Lynch Scott was born here.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] President of the Treasury Board Tony Clement spent time as a Brampton MPP.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] John McDermid held various cabinet positions under Brian Mulroney, Bal Gosal Minister of State-Sport, and former Mayor Linda Jeffrey held cabinet positions at the provincial level.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Incumbent mayor Patrick Brown served as leader of the Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario and as leader of the official opposition from 2015 until 2018 prior to serving as mayor.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] He was also a federal MP and provincial MPP, but not for Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Ruby Dhalla represented the riding of Brampton—Springdale in the Canadian House of Commons from 2004 to 2011 as a member of the Liberal Party.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Dhalla and British Columbia Conservative MP Nina Grewal were the first Sikh women to serve in the Canadian House of Commons.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Parm Gill was elected as the member of parliament from the Conservative Party of Canada for the riding of Brampton-Springdale in 2011, who was also appointed as the Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister of Veteran Affairs in 2013.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Jagmeet Singh began his political career in Brampton running in two elections in 2011, defeated in the federal election in May but elected Member of Provincial Parliament for Bramalea—Gore—Malton in October.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] In 2015 he became deputy leader of the Ontario New Democratic Party.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] In 2017 he became leader of the federal NDP, the first member of a visible minority to become permanent leader of a major federal party in Canada.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Authors born in or living in Brampton include Rohinton Mistry, Jesse Thistle, Edo Van Belkom and Rupi Kaur (poet).
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Visual arts notables from Brampton include etcher Caroline Helena Armington, Ronald Bloore, Member of the Order of Canada; Organiser and member of the "Regina Five" (1960), watercolourist Jack Reid, and William Ronald, who was raised in town.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Animators David Feiss and Jay Stephens grew up here.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Music acts from Brampton include Punk band The Flatliners, Indie Rock band Moneen, R&B singer Keshia Chanté, country singer Johnny Reid, "Metal Queen" Lee Aaron and pop singer Alyssa Reid.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Country singer and "World Champion Yodeller" Donn Reynolds lived here from 1969 to 1997.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Barry Stock, guitarist from Three Days Grace was raised in Brampton, and currently resides in Caledon.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Singer Alessia Cara, hip-hop artist Roy Woods, and hip-hop artist Tory Lanez were also born in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Hip-hop record producer WondaGurl was also born in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Two notable comedians hail from Brampton: Scott Thompson and Russell Peters.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Comedic actor Michael Cera was born and raised in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] The twin actors Shawn Ashmore and Aaron Ashmore (*Smallville*) are Brampton-raised.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] The sibling actors Tyler Labine (*Mad Love*) and Kyle Labine were born in Brampton.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Other Brampton-born or affiliated actors include Paulo Costanzo, Jordan Gavaris, Gemini Award winner Kris Lemche, Lara Jean Chorostecki, Sabrina Grdevich, Nicole Lyn, actor and producer David J.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Phillips, reality TV star and art dealer Billy Jamieson, performer George R.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Robertson, and performer Sidhu Moose Wala.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Others include voice actor Brenna O'Brien, and on-air media personalities Cassie Campbell, Chris Connor, Chris Cuthbert and Scott McGillivray.
[src:dodge-super-bee/brampton-ontario-p02] Brampton has two sister cities as well as active economic, historic, and cultural relationships with others.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The **Dodge Super Bee** is a mid-sized muscle car marketed by Dodge, which was produced for the 1968 through 1971 model years.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] In Mexico, the Super Bee model was based on a compact Chrysler platform and was marketed from 1970 until 1980.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Super Bee model name returned on versions of the Dodge Charger (LX) four-door sedans for the 2007, 2008, 2009, 2012, 2013, and 2023 model years.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The original Dodge Super Bee was based on the Dodge Coronet two-door coupe, and was produced from 1968 until 1970.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] It was Dodge's low-priced muscle car and rebranded and mildly distinguished from the Plymouth Road Runner.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The origin of the name, "Super Bee", has its basis in the "B" Body designation pertinent to Chrysler's mid-sized cars, including the Road Runner and Charger.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Plymouth's Road Runner sales were enough to have Dodge Division General Manager, Robert McCurry, request a similar model from the Dodge Styling office.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Winn, won a "contest" with the name "Super Bee" and a new logo design based on the Dodge "Scat Pack" Bee medallion.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The design of the first Super Bee was influenced by the 1968 Coronet convertible and the show car's interior was built by the Alexander Brothers.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The show car was introduced at the 1968 Detroit Auto Show.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Although the two cars are similar in external appearance, the Super Bee was slightly heavier - approx.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] 65 lb (29 kg) - and rode on a 117-inch (2,972 mm) wheelbase compared to the Road Runner's 116 in (2,946 mm) wheelbase.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] In addition to minor external differences, such as larger rear wheel openings, the bumblebee tail stripe and fancier grille, and the taillight ornamentation, the Super Bee also used actual diecast chrome-plated "Bee" medallions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] These three-dimensional medallions were prominently mounted in a raised position in the grille/hood area and the trunklid/taillight area of the car throughout the first three years of production.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Super Bee used a dash cluster from the Dodge Charger, while the 4-speed manual transmission cars received a Hurst Competition-Plus shifter with Hurst linkage; this shifter compared to the Road Runner's less expensive Inland shifter and linkage.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Due to the higher-quality accessories attached to the Super Bee, the car was sold at a higher price in comparison to the Plymouth version and this had a negative effect on sales.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Super Bee was available with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] This option raised the price by 33%, and 125 were sold.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The 1968 model was available only as a two-door coupe, with two engine options, the base 335 hp (250 kW) 383 Magnum, and the 426 Hemi, rated at 425 hp (317 kW).
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Super Bee included a heavy-duty suspension, an optional Mopar A833 4-speed manual transmission, and high-performance tires.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Outside, a stripe (with the bee logo) was wrapped around the tail.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] A hardtop version joined the existing pillared coupe body in 1969 and the front and rear ends received revisions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The front end featured a more aggressive design with a 'squeezed' appearance to the surround of the headlights and in towards the central grille section while the rear end featured new horizontally-themed tail lights.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] A new optional twin-scooped air induction hood known as the "Ramcharger" became available.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] This particular option was coded N96 and was the counterpart to the Plymouth Road Runner's "Coyote Duster" air induction hood.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The "Ramcharger" hood featured forward-facing scoops.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] A "six-pack" (three two-barrel Holley carburetors) version of Dodge's 440 cu in (7.2 L) engine was added to the offering list mid-year rated at 390 bhp (395 PS; 291 kW) at 4700 rpm and 490 lb⋅ft (664 N⋅m) at 3600 rpm of torque.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The option code for this was A12, which changed the 5th digit of the VIN to M.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] These special order 1969 1/2 Dodge Super Bees are known as A12 M-code cars.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The A12 package also equipped the cars with a Dana 60 axle with a 4:10 gear-ratio, heavy duty automatic transmission or a 4-speed manual, and a 'lift off' flat black scooped hood.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Other components to the A12 package included heavy duty internal engine parts, black steel wheels with performance G70x15 tires, and heavy-duty 11-inch drum brakes.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] A total of 1,907 A12 M-code 440 Six Pack 1969 1/2 Dodge Super Bees were produced.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] This option fell half-way between the standard engine and the Hemi as a US$463 option.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The 1969 model year included the base 383 Magnum, 440 Six Pack, and the 426 Hemi.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The 440 Magnum (4bbl) was reserved for the Coronet R/T.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] For the 1970 model, the Super Bee received a redesign and a new front-end that consisted of a twin-looped front bumper that Dodge Public Relations referred to as "bumble bee wings".
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Sales fell for the year from 15,506 in 1970 to 5,054 in 1971—because of, or in spite of, this new look, with another sales pressure coming from higher insurance rates for performance cars; the similar Plymouth Road Runner and Plymouth Duster both experienced similar sales issues.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] In addition to the new looks, engine choices and "ramcharger" hood carried over from 1969, the 1970 cars from Dodge featured several new or improved options.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] For example, a "C- stripe" variant of the bumble stripe was offered, in addition to new high-back bucket seats, a steering column-mounted ignition and a "pistol grip" Hurst shifter on four-speed models.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The 1971 Coronet line was built in four-door sedan and station wagon body versions, the Super Bee model was moved to the platform used by the Charger.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Since an *R/T* muscle car version of the Charger already existed, the Super Bee was promoted as the low-priced model in the line, selling at US$3,271.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Production numbers of the Super Bee reached 5,054, including 22 with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] 1971 was the first and only year that a small block engine (340 4-bbl) became available in the Super Bee.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The moniker was discontinued in the domestic market until the 2007 Super Bee, a version of the LX platform based Charger SRT8.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] In 1970, Chrysler of Mexico introduced the new Dodge Super Bee as a replacement for the company's previous sports car product, the Plymouth Barracuda.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] As the production and sale costs of the third-generation Barracuda in Mexico were too high, Dodge adapted the semi-fastback A-Body platform and introduced the Super Bee at the beginning.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Super Bee was only available with the V8 318 engine (270 hp) and either a four-speed or three-speed manual transmission.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The 1970 model was virtually identical to the Plymouth Duster (known in Mexico as the "Valiant Duster"), with side stripes and the Super Bee decals.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] In 1971, Dodge differentiated the Super Bee from the Duster, by using the grille from the American Dodge Demon.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] However, in 1976, the final year for the A body cars, the front grille of the Plymouth model became the standard design.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Valiant Super Bee was equipped with the 318 V8 engine, with 270 hp, from 1970 to 1974; from 1975 to 1976, it contained the 360 V8 engine, with 270 hp—these engines had more power in Mexico than in the US, as Mexican anti-pollution laws were less strict in comparison to the US.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Over the years, these models only received minor changes, such as new grilles, rear panels, and tail lights.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The first generation was produced from 1970 to 1976; during the fall of 1975, Chrysler introduced the new F Body cars: the Dodge Aspen and Plymouth Volare (as 1976 models), while the Aspen R/T and Volare Road Runner were released as the sports versions.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Chrysler de México continued to use old model names after they were dropped in the U.S. marketplace.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Dodge Aspen and Plymouth Volare were sold in Mexico as the Dodge Dart and the Valiant Volare, and the sports version was named the Valiant Super Bee.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Mexican Dodge Dart consisted of the front of the US Plymouth Volare and the rear of the Dodge Aspen, while the Mexican Valiant Volare and the Dodge Super Bee consisted of the front of the Dodge Aspen and the rear of the US Plymouth Volare.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Super Bee was equipped with the 360 V8 engine and 270 hp, the three-speed Torque Flite automatic transmission (or the four-speed manual transmission), sports wide wheels, front spoiler, and a rear spoiler-style Trans Am with the Super Bee spelling (with an optional blind in the rear window).
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The federal highway patrol used Super Bee as a squad car.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] For the 1980-model year, the Super Bee received a new front with rectangular headlamps.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] For the 1981 model year, the Dodge Diplomat was introduced in Mexico, under the name of Dodge Dart (replacing the Dodge Aspen), and was considered a luxury car.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] A new sports version of the 1981 Dodge Dart replaced the Valiant Super Bee and is now called the Dodge Magnum—the version consisted of the 360 V8 engine and 270 hp, with variations in transmissions: The three-speed automatic and the four-speed manual.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] A new 2007 Super Bee model was introduced at the 2006 North American International Auto Show.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] It is based on the Dodge Charger SRT8 and its exterior consists of special "Detonator Yellow" paint, a "Flat Black" hood, and fender "decals".
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The production version consisted of a hood decal, rather than an entirely black hood, and the "hockey stick" stripe on the side was changed from solid black to a dashed black stripe positioned at the bottom of the exterior.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The wheels are fully polished and do not contain the silver-painted areas of the "stock" SRT8 Charger.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The interior is completely black, with yellow accent stitching on the seats and shift knob; this is unlike the "two-tone" interior of the standard SRT8 Charger which consists of red stitching (this is the only model that contains such an interior, as the Charger interior changed in 2008).
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The appearance of the shifter "bezel" and center console resembles that of carbon fiber, and the Super Bee logo appears in the instrument cluster during "power-up", instead of the SRT logo.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] It is a limited edition car, with 1,000 made for the 2007 model year with build dates as early as August 2006.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Each car is built in Brampton Assembly Plant, then shipped to Windsor to have decals applied and a unique number plaque on the passenger side of the dash.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The number sequence on the dash does not necessarily follow build order, as multiple "Bees" were shipped to Windsor by car carrier, and the order was not retained.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] It uses the same 425 bhp (317 kW; 431 PS) Hemi 6.1 L engine as the SRT8 versions of the Dodge Charger, Dodge Magnum, Dodge Challenger and Chrysler 300C.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] For the 2008 model year, the Super Bee was only made in "B5 Blue Pearl Coat" (sometimes listed as "Surf Blue Pearl"), reminiscent of the blue used by Chrysler vehicles in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Instead of fully polished SRT8 Charger wheels, the "pockets" are painted black on the ALCOA wheels.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] Blue accent stitching inside replaces the yellow found on the seats and steering wheel, but the Charger's interior was changed for 2008, so the dash and console are different than the 2007 version interior.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] This year also introduced touch screen navigation and an in-dash DVD player.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] It was based on the SRT8 model using the 6.1 L engine and had a production run of 1,000 units.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] For the 2009 model year, the Super Bee was only made in "Hemi Orange Pearl Coat", and was based on the SRT8 model.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] The Super Bee used the 6.1 L engine, and had a production run of 425.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] This year also introduced touch screen navigation and an in-dash DVD player with a hard drive.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] ALCOA wheels were standard this year only.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] In 2011, the Super Bee SRT8 returned as a 2012 model on the redesigned Dodge Charger with the 392 Hemi engine (6.4 L) in "Stinger Yellow" and "Pitch Black" colors, with additional colors being added for 2013 and 2014.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] This version of the Super Bee returned to the name's roots as a "budget" muscle car, devoid of most luxury items yet maintaining high performance in the form of a less expensive SRT model.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] In March 2023, Dodge confirmed it would be discontinuing the Charger and Challenger lineup due to emissions standards.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] This prompted Dodge to release many "Last Call" special editions for the LD Charger and LA Challenger's final model year, in which the Super Bee would return to the Charger lineup for the first time since 2014.
[src:dodge-super-bee/dodge-super-bee] This iteration of the Charger was a package for the 392 Scat Pack model, which itself had replaced the 2012-14 LD Super Bee, and production was limited to 1,000 units.
